Mounting — connecting a filesystem to the tree.

You've formatted a filesystem, but it's still not usable, because Linux has a single unified directory tree, and your filesystem isn't part of it yet. To make it usable, you mount it: you attach it at some directory in the tree. The mount command attaches a filesystem at a directory, and umount detaches it.

The basic form is sudo mount, the device, then the mount point. So sudo mount slash-dev-sdb-one on slash-mnt-data attaches that filesystem there. Add dash-o ro to mount it read-only. And to detach, sudo umount, giving either the mount point or the device. One requirement: the mount point has to already exist as a directory, so you mkdir it first if needed. And be aware that anything that was previously visible at that directory gets hidden underneath the mount until you unmount.

There are several mount options worth knowing, and they go after dash-o, comma-separated. ro and rw are read-only and read-write, with read-write being the default. noatime tells the kernel not to update file access times on every read, which is a nice free performance win. nosuid ignores SUID bits on that filesystem, noexec forbids executing binaries from it, and nodev ignores device nodes; those three are common hardening options for untrusted media. And defaults is a shorthand bundle: read-write, suid, dev, exec, auto, and async.

There are also three flavours of "what" you can mount. First, a real block device, like slash-dev-sdb-one. Second, a virtual kernel filesystem, like proc mounted on slash-proc, or tmpfs mounted on slash-tmp; here the source isn't a device at all, it's a kernel filesystem type. And third, a bind mount, done with mount dash-dash-bind, which makes the same data appear at a second path in the tree; that's used heavily by containers.

To see what's currently mounted, you have a few choices, but findmnt is the friendliest, giving you a clean tree; df dash-h-capital-T also shows usage and filesystem type alongside. One last thing to remember: mounts made this way are temporary. They vanish on reboot. Making them permanent is the job of etc-fstab, which is the very next section.
